# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: skaffold
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] The earliest known work (1989) on continuous integration was the Infuse environment developed by G.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] In 1997, Kent Beck and Ron Jeffries invented extreme programming (XP) while on the Chrysler Comprehensive Compensation System project, including continuous integration.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] Beck published about continuous integration in 1998, emphasising the importance of face-to-face communication over technological support.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] In 1999, Beck elaborated more in his first full book on Extreme Programming.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] CruiseControl, one of the first open-source CI tools, was released in 2001.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] In 2010, Timothy Fitz published an article detailing how IMVU's engineering team had built and been using the first practical CD system.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] While his post was originally met with skepticism, it quickly caught on and found widespread adoption as part of the lean software development methodology, also based on IMVU.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] The core activities of CI are that developers co-locate code changes in a shared, integration area frequently and that the resulting integrated codebase is verified for correctness.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] The first part generally involves merging changes to a common version control branch.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] The second part generally involves automated processes including: building, testing and many other processes.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] Typically, a server builds from the integration area frequently, i.e. after each commit or periodically, like once a day.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] The server may perform quality control checks such as running unit tests and collect software quality metrics via processes such as static analysis and performance testing.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] Build automation tools automate building.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI recommend that a single command should have the capability of building the system.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] Automation often includes automating the integration, which often includes deployment into a production-like environment.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] In many cases, the build script not only compiles binaries but also generates documentation, website pages, statistics and distribution media (such as Debian DEB, Red Hat RPM or Windows MSI files).
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] CI requires the version control system to support atomic commits; in other words, all of a developer's changes are handled as a single commit.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] When making a code change, a developer creates a branch that is a copy of the current codebase.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] As other changes are committed to the repository, this copy diverges from the latest version.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] The longer development continues on a branch without merging to the integration branch, the greater the risk of multiple integration conflicts and failures when the developer branch is eventually merged back.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] When developers submit code to the repository they must first update their code to reflect the changes in the repository since they took their copy.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] The more changes the repository contains, the more work developers must do before submitting their own changes.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] Eventually, the repository may become so different from the developers' baselines that they enter what is sometimes referred to as "merge hell", or "integration hell", where the time it takes to integrate exceeds the time it took to make their original changes.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI suggest that developers should use test-driven development and to ensure that all unit tests pass locally before committing to the integration branch so that one developer's work does not break another developer's copy.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] Incomplete features can be disabled before committing, using feature toggles.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] Continuous delivery ensures the software checked in on an integration branch is always in a state that can be deployed to users, and continuous deployment automates the deployment process.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI recommend storing all files and information needed for building in version control (for git a *repository*), and that the system should be buildable from a fresh checkout and not require additional dependencies.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] Martin Fowler recommends that all developers commit to the same integration branch.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] Developers can reduce the effort of resolving conflicting changes by synchronizing changes with each other frequently, at least daily.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] Checking in a week's worth of work risks conflict both in likelihood of occurrence and complexity to resolve.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] Relatively small conflicts are significantly easier to resolve than larger ones.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] Integrating (committing) changes at least once a day is considered good practice, and more often better.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] Building daily, if not more often, is generally recommended.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] The system should build commits to the current working version to verify that they integrate correctly.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] A common practice is to use Automated Continuous Integration, although this may be done manually.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] Automated continuous integration employs a continuous integration server or daemon to monitor the revision control system for changes, then automatically run the build process.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] When fixing a bug, it is a good practice to push a test case that reproduces the bug.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] This prevents the fix from being reverted and the bug from reappearing, which is known as a regression.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] The build needs to complete rapidly so that if there is a problem with integration, it is quickly identified.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] Having a test environment can lead to failures in tested systems when they deploy in the production environment because the production environment may differ from the test environment in a significant way.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] However, building a replica of a production environment is cost-prohibitive.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] Instead, the test environment or a separate pre-production environment ("staging") should be built to be a scalable version of the production environment to alleviate costs while maintaining technology stack composition and nuances.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] Within these test environments, service virtualisation is commonly used to obtain on-demand access to dependencies (e.g., APIs, third-party applications, services, mainframes, etc.) that are beyond the team's control, still evolving, or too complex to configure in a virtual test lab.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] Making builds readily available to stakeholders and testers can reduce the amount of rework necessary when rebuilding a feature that doesn't meet requirements.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] Additionally, early testing reduces the chances that defects survive until deployment.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] Finding errors earlier can reduce the amount of work necessary to resolve them.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] All programmers should start the day by updating the project from the repository.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] That way, they will all stay up to date.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] It should be easy to find out whether the build breaks and, if so, who made the relevant change and what that change was.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] Most CI systems allow the running of scripts after a build finishes.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] In most situations, it is possible to write a script to deploy the application to a live test server that everyone can look at.
[src:skaffold/continuous-integration] A further advance in this way of thinking is continuous deployment, which calls for the software to be deployed directly into production, often with additional automation to prevent defects or regressions.
[src:skaffold/devops] Although debated, DevOps is generally characterized by three key principles: shared ownership, workflow automation, and rapid feedback.
[src:skaffold/devops] However, the term is used in multiple contexts.
[src:skaffold/devops] At its most successful, DevOps is a combination of specific practices, culture change, and tools.
[src:skaffold/devops] Proposals to combine software development methodologies with deployment and operations concepts first appeared in the late 80s and early 90s.
[src:skaffold/devops] In 2009, the first DevOps Days conference was held in Ghent, Belgium.
[src:skaffold/devops] The conference was founded by Belgian IT consultant and practitioner Patrick Debois.
[src:skaffold/devops] The conference has now spread to other countries.
[src:skaffold/devops] In 2012, the first "State of DevOps" report was published by Alanna Brown at Puppet Labs.
[src:skaffold/devops] In 2016, the DORA metrics for throughput (deployment frequency, lead time for changes), and stability (mean time to recover, change failure rate) were published in that year's State of DevOps report.
[src:skaffold/devops] However, the research methodology and metrics were criticized by some experts.
[src:skaffold/devops] In response to these criticisms, the 2023 State of DevOps report published changes that updated the stability metric "mean time to recover" to "failed deployment recovery time" acknowledging the confusion the previous metric had caused.
[src:skaffold/devops] The 2024 report restructured the metrics framework by moving failed deployment recovery time from stability to throughput and introducing a new "rework rate" metric measuring the proportion of unplanned deployments made to fix user-visible issues.
[src:skaffold/devops] In 2025, DORA moved away from sorting teams into performance tiers and instead introduced seven team archetypes that combine delivery metrics with human factors like burnout, friction, and perceived value.
[src:skaffold/devops] DevOps Research and Assessment (DORA) has developed a set of metrics which are intended to measure software development efficiency and reliability.
[src:skaffold/devops] Many of the ideas fundamental to DevOps are similar to other well-known practices, such as Lean and Deming's Plan-Do-Check-Act cycle, The Toyota Way, and the Agile approach of breaking down components and batch sizes.
[src:skaffold/devops] Contrary to the "top-down" prescriptive approach and rigid framework of ITIL in the 1990s, DevOps is "bottom-up" and flexible, having been created by software engineers for their own needs.
[src:skaffold/devops] The motivations for what has become modern DevOps and several standard DevOps practices such as automated build and test, continuous integration, and continuous delivery originated in the Agile world, which informally dates to the 1990s and formally to 2001.
[src:skaffold/devops] Agile development teams using methods such as extreme programming couldn't "satisfy the customer through early and continuous delivery of valuable software" unless they took responsibility for operations and infrastructure for their applications, automating much of that work.
[src:skaffold/devops] Because Scrum emerged as the dominant Agile framework in the early 2000s and it omitted the engineering practices that were part of many Agile teams, the momentum to automate operations and infrastructure functions splintered from Agile and expanded into what has become modern DevOps.
[src:skaffold/devops] Today, DevOps focuses on deploying methodology-agnostic, developed software.
[src:skaffold/devops] ArchOps starts from software architecture artifacts instead of source code for operational deployment, as opposed to DevOps.
[src:skaffold/devops] ArchOps holds that architectural models are first-class entities in software development, deployment, and operations.
[src:skaffold/devops] CI/CD is as critical to DevOps success as automation.
[src:skaffold/devops] Additionally, improved collaboration and communication between and within teams helps them achieve faster time to market with reduced risks.
[src:skaffold/devops] Database DevOps applies DevOps and CI/CD principles directly to database development and operations.
[src:skaffold/devops] Integrating schema changes, migrations, reference data, and other data-layer updates into the same version-controlled and automated pipelines used for application code enables more reliable deployments.
[src:skaffold/devops] This approach also enables improved coordination between application and data changes.
[src:skaffold/devops] Typical database DevOps practices include placing database schema definitions under version control, applying automated tests (such as unit tests or migration validation) to database changes, and deploying those changes through CI/CD pipelines.
[src:skaffold/devops] These practices reduce what is commonly referred to as "schema drift" between development and production systems and lower the risk of deployment failures.
[src:skaffold/devops] Mobile DevOps is a methodology that applies DevOps' principles to the development of mobile applications.
[src:skaffold/devops] Traditional DevOps focuses on streamlining the general software development process, but mobile development has unique challenges that require a tailored approach.
[src:skaffold/devops] Mobile DevOps is not simply a branch of DevOps specific to mobile app development, but rather an extension and reinterpretation of the DevOps philosophy tailored to mobile's specific requirements.
[src:skaffold/devops] In 2003, Google developed site reliability engineering (SRE), an approach for releasing new features continuously into large-scale, high-availability systems while maintaining a high-quality end-user experience.
[src:skaffold/devops] While SRE predates the development of DevOps, they are generally viewed as being related to each other.
[src:skaffold/devops] Some of the original authors of the discipline consider SRE as an implementation of DevOps.
[src:skaffold/devops] The Toyota Production System (TPS), inspired lean thinking with its focus on continuous improvement, kaizen, flow, and small batches.
[src:skaffold/devops] The andon cord principle of creating fast feedback, swarming, and solving problems stems from TPS.
[src:skaffold/devops] As its name implies, DevSecOps integrates DevOps within security practices.
[src:skaffold/devops] Contrary to a traditional centralized security team model, each delivery team is empowered to factor the correct security controls into their software delivery.
[src:skaffold/devops] Teams perform tests and implement security practices earlier in the development lifecycle, hence the term "shift left".
[src:skaffold/devops] Security is tested in three main areas: static, software composition, and dynamic.
[src:skaffold/devops] Checking software statically via static application security testing (SAST) is white-box testing with special focus on security.
[src:skaffold/devops] Depending on the programming language, different tools are needed to do such static code analysis.
[src:skaffold/devops] The software composition is analyzed, especially libraries, and the version of each component is checked against vulnerability lists published by CERT and other expert groups.
[src:skaffold/devops] When giving software to clients, library licenses and their match to the license of the software distributed are in focus, especially copyleft licenses.
[src:skaffold/devops] In dynamic testing, also called black-box testing, software is tested without knowing its inner functions.
[src:skaffold/devops] In DevSecOps this practice may be referred to as dynamic application security testing (DAST) or penetration testing.
[src:skaffold/devops] The goal is early detection of defects including cross-site scripting and SQL injection vulnerabilities.
[src:skaffold/devops] Often, detected defects from static and dynamic testing are triaged and categorized under taxonomies like the Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE), maintained by the Mitre Corporation.
[src:skaffold/devops] This facilitates the prioritization of security bug fixes and also allows frequently recurring weaknesses to be fixed with recommended mitigations.
[src:skaffold/devops] As of 2025, CWE maintained its own list of frequently-occurring weaknesses, the CWE Top 25.
[src:skaffold/devops] In addition, organizations like Open Worldwide Application Security Project (OWASP) maintain lists of industry-wide frequently recurring software weaknesses.
[src:skaffold/devops] DevSecOps has also been described as a cultural shift involving a holistic approach to producing secure software by integrating security education, security by design, and security automation.
[src:skaffold/devops] DevOps initiatives can change how a company's operations, developers, and testers collaborate during development and delivery processes.
[src:skaffold/devops] DevOps attempts to support consistency, reliability, and efficiency within an organization.
[src:skaffold/devops] This is usually enabled by a shared code repository or version control.
[src:skaffold/devops] Many organizations use version control to facilitate DevOps automation technologies like virtual machines, containerization (or OS-level virtualization), and CI/CD, with the Git version control system and the GitHub platform referenced as examples.
[src:skaffold/devops] It takes its name from the popular version control system Git, and the specific state of deployment configuration is also version-controlled.
[src:skaffold/devops] Configuration changes can be managed using code review practices, and can be rolled back using version-controlling.
[src:skaffold/devops] Essentially, all of the changes to a code are tracked, bookmarked, and making any updates to the history can be made easier.
[src:skaffold/devops] DataOps incorporates the Agile methodology to shorten the cycle time of analytics development in alignment with business goals.
[src:skaffold/devops] DevOps focuses on continuous delivery by leveraging on-demand IT resources and by automating test and deployment of software.
[src:skaffold/devops] This merging of software *development* and IT *operations* has improved velocity, quality, predictability and scale of software engineering and deployment.
[src:skaffold/devops] Borrowing methods from DevOps, DataOps seeks to bring these same improvements to data analytics.
[src:skaffold/devops] DataOps utilizes statistical process control (SPC) to monitor and control the data analytics pipeline.
[src:skaffold/devops] With SPC in place, the data flowing through an operational system is constantly monitored and verified.
[src:skaffold/devops] If an anomaly occurs, the data analytics team can be notified with an automated alert.
[src:skaffold/devops] DataOps is not tied to a particular technology, architecture, tool, language or framework.
[src:skaffold/devops] The best DataOps tools promote collaboration, orchestration, quality, security, access and ease of use.
[src:skaffold/devops] DataOps was first introduced by InformationWeek contributing editor Lenny Liebmann in a blog post on the IBM Big Data & Analytics Hub titled "3 reasons why DataOps is essential for big data success" on June 19, 2014.
[src:skaffold/devops] The term DataOps was later popularized by Andy Palmer of Tamr and Steph Locke.
[src:skaffold/devops] DataOps is a moniker for "Data Operations." 2017 was a significant year for DataOps, with significant ecosystem development, analyst coverage, increased keyword searches, surveys, publications, and open source projects.
[src:skaffold/devops] Gartner placed DataOps on the Hype Cycle for Data Management in 2018.
[src:skaffold/devops] The total world data volume is forecast to grow at a rate of 32% CAGR to 180 Zettabytes by 2025 (Source: IDC).
[src:skaffold/devops] DataOps seeks to provide the tools, processes, and organizational structures to accommodate this significant increase in data.
[src:skaffold/devops] Automation streamlines data preboarding, ingestion, and the management of large integrated databases, freeing the data team to develop new analytics in a more efficient and effective way.
[src:skaffold/devops] DataOps seeks to increase velocity, reliability, and quality of data analytics.
[src:skaffold/devops] It emphasizes communication, collaboration, integration, automation, measurement and cooperation between data scientists, analysts, data/ETL (extract, transform, load) engineers, information technology (IT), and quality assurance/governance.
[src:skaffold/init] `skaffold init` helps you get started using Skaffold by running you through a wizard and generating the required `skaffold.yaml` file in the root of your project directory.
[src:skaffold/init] The generated `skaffold.yaml` defines your build and deploy config.
[src:skaffold/init] `skaffold init` walks your project directory and looks for any build configuration files such as `Dockerfile`, `build.gradle/pom.xml`, `package.json`, `requirements.txt` or `go.mod`.
[src:skaffold/init] `init` skips files that are larger than 500MB.
[src:skaffold/init] If there are multiple build configuration files, Skaffold will prompt you to pair your build configuration files with any images detected in your deploy configuration.
[src:skaffold/init] if none of the suggested options are correct, or this image is not built by any of your source code.
[src:skaffold/init] If this image is one you want Skaffold to build, you’ll need to manually set up the build configuration for this artifact.
[src:skaffold/init] `skaffold` init also recognizes Maven and Gradle projects, and will auto-suggest the `jib` builder.
[src:skaffold/init] `skaffold init` support bootstrapping projects set up to deploy with `kubectl` or `kustomize`.
[src:skaffold/init] For projects deploying straight through `kubectl`, Skaffold will walk through all the `yaml` files in your project and find valid Kubernetes manifest files.
[src:skaffold/init] These files will be added to `deploy` config in `skaffold.yaml`.
[src:skaffold/init] For projects deploying with `kustomize`, Skaffold will scan your project and look for `kustomization.yaml`s as well as Kubernetes manifests.
[src:skaffold/init] When overlay directories are found, these will be listed in the generated Skaffold config as `paths` in the `kustomize` deploy stanza.
[src:skaffold/init] However, it generally does not make sense to have multiple overlays applied at the same time, so **Skaffold will attempt to choose a default overlay, and put each other overlay into its own profile**.
[src:skaffold/init] beta `skaffold init` allows for use of a `--generate-manifests` flag, which will try to generate basic kubernetes manifests for a user’s project to help get things up and running.
[src:skaffold/init] If bringing a project to skaffold that has no kubernetes manifests yet, it may be helpful to run `skaffold init` with this flag.
[src:skaffold/init] `skaffold init` allows for use of a `--force` flag, which removes the prompts from vanilla `skaffold init`, and allows skaffold to make a best effort attempt to automatically generate a config for your project.
[src:skaffold/init] In a situation where one image is detected, but multiple possible builders are detected, skaffold will choose a builder as follows: Docker > Jib > Ko > Bazel > Buildpacks.
[src:skaffold/init] `skaffold init` also exposes an API which tools like IDEs can integrate with via flags.
[src:skaffold/init] Given a pairing between the image names (artifacts) and build definitions (e.g.
[src:skaffold/init] Dockerfiles), generate Skaffold `build` config for a given artifact.
[src:skaffold/init] Analyze API walks through all files in your project workspace and looks for `Dockerfile` files.
[src:skaffold/init] To generate a skaffold `build` config, use the `--artifact` flag per artifact.
[src:skaffold/init] For multiple artifacts, use `--artifact` multiple times.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The name *Kubernetes* comes from the Ancient Greek term κυβερνήτης, *kubernḗtēs* (helmsman, pilot), which is also the origin of the words *cybernetics* and (through Latin) *governor*.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] "Kubernetes" is often abbreviated with the numerical contraction "K8s", meaning "the letter K, followed by 8 letters, followed by s".
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Kubernetes assembles one or more computers, either virtual machines or bare metal, into a cluster which can run workloads in containers.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] It works with various container runtimes, such as containerd and CRI-O.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Its suitability for running and managing workloads of all sizes and styles has led to its widespread adoption in clouds and data centers.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] There are multiple distributions of this platform—from independent software vendors (ISVs) as well as hosted-on-cloud offerings from all the major public cloud vendors.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The software consists of a control plane and nodes on which the actual applications run.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] It includes tools like `kubeadm` and `kubectl` which can be used to interact with its REST-based API.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced by Google on June 6, 2014.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The project was conceived and created by Google employees Joe Beda, Brendan Burns, and Craig McLuckie.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Others at Google soon joined to help build the project including Ville Aikas, Dawn Chen, Brian Grant, Tim Hockin, and Daniel Smith.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Other companies such as Red Hat and CoreOS joined the effort soon after, with notable contributors such as Clayton Coleman and Kelsey Hightower.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The design and development of Kubernetes was inspired by Google's Borg cluster manager and based on Promise Theory.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Many of its top contributors had previously worked on Borg; they codenamed Kubernetes "Project 7" after the *Star Trek* ex-Borg character Seven of Nine and gave its logo a seven-spoked ship's wheel (designed by Tim Hockin).
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Unlike Borg, which was written in C++, Kubernetes is written in the Go language.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced in June, 2014 and version 1.0 was released on July 21, 2015.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Google worked with the Linux Foundation to form the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) and offered Kubernetes as the seed technology.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Google was already offering a managed Kubernetes service, GKE, and Red Hat was supporting Kubernetes as part of OpenShift since the inception of the Kubernetes project in 2014.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] On March 6, 2018, Kubernetes Project reached ninth place in the list of GitHub projects by the number of commits, and second place in authors and issues, after the Linux kernel.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Until version 1.18, Kubernetes followed an N-2 support policy, meaning that the three most recent minor versions receive security updates and bug fixes.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Starting with version 1.19, Kubernetes follows an N-3 support policy.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines a set of building blocks ("primitives") that collectively provide mechanisms that deploy, maintain, and scale applications based on CPU, memory or custom metrics.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Kubernetes is loosely coupled and extensible to meet the needs of different workloads.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The internal components as well as extensions and containers that run on Kubernetes rely on the Kubernetes API.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The platform exerts its control over compute and storage resources by defining resources as objects, which can then be managed as such.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Kubernetes follows the primary/replica architecture.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The components of Kubernetes can be divided into those that manage an individual node and those that are part of the control plane.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The Kubernetes master node handles the Kubernetes control plane of the cluster, managing its workload and directing communication across the system.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The Kubernetes control plane consists of various components such as TLS encryption, role-based access control (RBAC) and a strong authentication method, network separation, each its own process, that can run both on a single master node or on multiple masters supporting high-availability clusters.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The various components of the Kubernetes control plane are as follows.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Etcd is a persistent, lightweight, distributed, key-value data store (originally developed as part of CoreOS).
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] It reliably stores the configuration data of the cluster, representing the overall state of the cluster at any given point of time.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Etcd favors consistency over availability in the event of a network partition (see CAP theorem).
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The consistency is crucial for correctly scheduling and operating services.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The API server serves the Kubernetes API using JSON over HTTP, which provides both the internal and external interface to Kubernetes.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The API server processes, validates REST requests, and updates the state of the API objects in etcd, thereby allowing clients to configure workloads and containers across worker nodes.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The API server uses etcd's watch API to monitor the cluster, roll out critical configuration changes, or restore any divergences of the state of the cluster back to the desired state as declared in etcd.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] As an example, a human operator may specify that three instances of a particular "pod" (see below) need to be running, and etcd stores this fact.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] If the Deployment controller finds that only two instances are running (conflicting with the etcd declaration), it schedules the creation of an additional instance of that pod.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The scheduler is an extensible component that selects the node that an unscheduled pod (the basic unit of workloads to be scheduled) runs on, based on resource availability and other constraints.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The scheduler tracks resource allocation on each node to ensure that workload is not scheduled in excess of available resources.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] For this purpose, the scheduler must know the resource requirements, resource availability, and other user-provided constraints or policy directives such as quality-of-service, affinity/anti-affinity requirements, and data locality.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The scheduler's role is to match resource "supply" to workload "demand".
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Kubernetes allows running multiple schedulers within a single cluster.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] As such, scheduler plug-ins may be developed and installed as in-process extensions to the native vanilla scheduler by running it as a separate scheduler, as long as they conform to the Kubernetes scheduling framework.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] This allows cluster administrators to extend or modify the behavior of the default Kubernetes scheduler according to their needs.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] A controller is a reconciliation loop that drives the actual cluster state toward the desired state, communicating with the API server to create, update, and delete the resources it manages (e.g., pods or service endpoints).
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] An example controller is a ReplicaSet controller, which handles replication and scaling by running a specified number of copies of a pod across the cluster.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The controller also handles creating replacement pods if the underlying node fails.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Other controllers that are part of the core Kubernetes system include a DaemonSet controller for running exactly one pod on every machine (or some subset of machines), and a Job controller for running pods that run to completion (e.g. as part of a batch job).
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Labels selectors often form part of the controller's definition that specify the set of pods that a controller manages.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The controller manager is a single process that manages several core Kubernetes controllers (including the examples described above), is distributed as part of the standard Kubernetes installation and responding to the loss of nodes.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Custom controllers may also be installed in the cluster, further allowing the behavior and API of Kubernetes to be extended when used in conjunction with custom resources (see custom resources, controllers and operators below).
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] A node, also known as a worker or a minion, is a machine where containers (workloads) are deployed.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Every node in the cluster must run a container runtime, as well as the below-mentioned components, for communication with the primary network configuration of these containers.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] kubelet is responsible for the running state of each node, ensuring that all containers on the node are healthy.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] It takes care of starting, stopping, and maintaining application containers organized into pods as directed by the control plane. kubelet monitors the state of a pod, and if not in the desired state, the pod re-deploys to the same node.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Node status is relayed every few seconds via heartbeat messages to the API server.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Once the control plane detects a node failure, a higher-level controller is expected to observe this state change and launch pods on another healthy node.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] A container runtime is responsible for the lifecycle of containers, including launching, reconciling and killing of containers. kubelet interacts with container runtimes via the Container Runtime Interface (CRI), which decouples the maintenance of core Kubernetes from the actual CRI implementation.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Originally, kubelet interfaced exclusively with the Docker runtime through a "dockershim".
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] However, from November 2020 up to April 2022, Kubernetes has deprecated the shim in favor of directly interfacing with the container through containerd, or replacing Docker with a runtime that is compliant with the Container Runtime Interface (CRI).
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] With the release of v1.24 in May 2022, the "dockershim" has been removed entirely.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Examples of popular container runtimes that are compatible with kubelet include containerd (initially supported via Docker) and CRI-O.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] kube-proxy is an implementation of a network proxy and a load balancer, and it supports the service abstraction along with the other networking operations.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] It is responsible for routing traffic to the appropriate container based on IP and port number of the incoming request.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, namespaces are utilized to segregate the resources it handles into distinct and non-intersecting collections.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] They are intended for use in environments with many users spread across multiple teams, or projects, or even separating environments like development, test, and production.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The basic scheduling unit in Kubernetes is a pod, which consists of one or more containers that are guaranteed to be co-located on the same node.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Each pod in Kubernetes is assigned a unique IP address within the cluster, allowing applications to use ports without the risk of conflict.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Within the pod, all containers can reference each other.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The container is the lowest level of a micro-service, which holds the running application, libraries, and their dependencies.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Kubernetes supports several abstractions of workloads that are at a higher level over simple pods.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] This allows users to declaratively define and manage these high-level abstractions, instead of having to manage individual pods by themselves.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Several of these abstractions, supported by a standard installation of Kubernetes, are described below.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] A ReplicaSet's purpose is to maintain a stable set of replica pods running at any given time.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] As such, it is often used to guarantee the availability of a specified number of identical Pods.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The ReplicaSet can also be said to be a grouping mechanism that lets Kubernetes maintain the number of instances that have been declared for a given pod.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The definition of a ReplicaSet uses a selector, whose evaluation will result in identifying all pods that are associated with it.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] A ReplicationController, similar to a ReplicaSet, serves the same purpose and behaves similarly to a ReplicaSet, which is to ensure that there will always be a specified number of pod replicas as desired.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The ReplicationController workload was the predecessor of a ReplicaSet, but was eventually deprecated in favor of ReplicaSet to make use of set-based label selectors.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Deployments are a higher-level management mechanism for ReplicaSets.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] While the ReplicaSet controller manages the scale of the ReplicaSet, the Deployment controller manages what happens to the ReplicaSet – whether an update has to be rolled out, or rolled back, etc.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] When Deployments are scaled up or down, this results in the declaration of the ReplicaSet changing, and this change in the declared state is managed by the ReplicaSet controller.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] StatefulSets are controllers that enforce the properties of uniqueness and ordering amongst instances of a pod, and can be used to run stateful applications.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] While scaling stateless applications is only a matter of adding more running pods, doing so for stateful workloads is harder, because the state needs to be preserved if a pod is restarted.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] If the application is scaled up or down, the state may need to be redistributed.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Databases are an example of stateful workloads.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] When run in high-availability mode, many databases come with the notion of a primary instance and secondary instances.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of ordering of instances is important.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Other applications like Apache Kafka distribute the data amongst their brokers; hence, one broker is not the same as another.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of instance uniqueness is important.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] DaemonSets are responsible for ensuring that a pod is created on every single node in the cluster.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Generally, most workloads scale in response to a desired replica count, depending on the availability and performance requirements as needed by the application.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] However, in other scenarios it may be necessary to deploy a pod to every single node in the cluster, scaling up the number of total pods as nodes are added and garbage collecting them as they are removed.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] This is particularly helpful for use cases where the workload has some dependency on the actual node or host machine, such as log collection, ingress controllers, and storage services.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] A Kubernetes service is a set of pods that work together, such as one tier of a multi-tier application.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The set of pods that constitute a service are defined by a label selector.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two modes of service discovery, using environment variables or using Kubernetes DNS.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Service discovery assigns a stable IP address and DNS name to the service, and load balances traffic in a round-robin manner to network connections of that IP address among the pods matching the selector (even as failures cause the pods to move from machine to machine).
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] By default a service is exposed inside a cluster (e.g., back end pods might be grouped into a service, with requests from the front-end pods load-balanced among them), but a service can also be exposed outside a cluster (e.g., for clients to reach front-end pods).
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Filesystems in the Kubernetes container provide ephemeral storage, by default.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] This means that a restart of the pod will wipe out any data on such containers, and therefore, this form of storage is quite limiting in anything but trivial applications.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] A Kubernetes volume provides persistent storage that exists for the lifetime of the pod itself.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] This storage can also be used as shared disk space for containers within the pod.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Volumes are mounted at specific mount points within the container, which are defined by the pod configuration, and cannot mount onto other volumes or link to other volumes.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The same volume can be mounted at different points in the file system tree by different containers.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] A common application challenge is deciding where to store and manage configuration information, some of which may contain sensitive data.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Configuration data can be anything as fine-grained as individual properties, or coarse-grained information like entire configuration files such as JSON or XML documents.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two closely related mechanisms to deal with this need, known as ConfigMaps and Secrets, both of which allow for configuration changes to be made without requiring an application rebuild.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The data from ConfigMaps and Secrets will be made available to every single instance of the application to which these objects have been bound via the Deployment.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] A Secret and/or a ConfigMap is sent to a node only if a pod on that node requires it, which will only be stored in memory on the node.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Once the pod that depends on the Secret or ConfigMap is deleted, the in-memory copy of all bound Secrets and ConfigMaps are deleted as well.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Mounted within a volume accessible within the container's filesystem, which supports automatic reloading without restarting the container.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The biggest difference between a Secret and a ConfigMap is that Secrets are specifically designed for containing secure and confidential data, although they are not encrypted at rest by default, and requires additional setup in order to fully secure the use of Secrets within the cluster.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Secrets are often used to store confidential or sensitive data like certificates, credentials to work with image registries, passwords, and ssh keys.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Kubernetes enables clients (users or internal components) to attach keys called labels to any API object in the system, such as pods and nodes.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Correspondingly, label selectors are queries against labels that resolve to matching objects.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] When a service is defined, one can define the label selectors that will be used by the service router/load balancer to select the pod instances that the traffic will be routed to.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Thus, simply changing the labels of the pods or changing the label selectors on the service can be used to control which pods get traffic and which don't, which can be used to support various deployment patterns like blue–green deployments or A/B testing.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] This capability to dynamically control how services utilize implementing resources provides a loose coupling within the infrastructure.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Just like labels, field selectors also let one select Kubernetes resources.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Unlike labels, the selection is based on the attribute values inherent to the resource being selected, rather than user-defined categorization.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] `metadata.name` and `metadata.namespace` are field selectors that will be present on all Kubernetes objects.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Other selectors that can be used depend on the object/resource type.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Add-ons are additional features of the Kubernetes cluster implemented as applications running within it.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The pods may be managed by Deployments, ReplicationControllers, and so on.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Cluster DNS is a DNS server, in addition to the other DNS server(s) in the environment, which serves DNS records for Kubernetes services.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Containers started by Kubernetes automatically include this DNS server in their DNS searches.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] This is a general purpose, web-based UI for Kubernetes clusters.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] It allows administrators to manage and troubleshoot applications running in the cluster, as well as the cluster itself.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Container Resource Monitoring records metrics about containers in a central database, and provides a UI for browsing that data.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Kubernetes cost monitoring applications allow breakdown of costs by pods, nodes, namespaces, and labels.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] To prevent the loss of event data in the event of node or pod failures, container logs can be saved to a central log store with a search/browsing interface.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides no native storage for log data, but one can integrate many existing logging solutions into the Kubernetes cluster.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Containers emerged as a way to make software portable.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The container contains all the packages needed to run a service.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The provided file system makes containers extremely portable and easy to use in development.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] A container can be moved from development to test or production with no or relatively few configuration changes.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Historically Kubernetes was suitable only for stateless services.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] However, many applications have a database, which requires persistence, leading to the creation of persistent storage for Kubernetes.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Implementing persistent storage for containers is one of the top challenges of Kubernetes administrators, DevOps and cloud engineers.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Containers may be ephemeral, but more and more of their data is not, so one needs to ensure the data's survival in case of container termination or hardware failure.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] When deploying containers with Kubernetes or containerized applications, organizations often realize that they need persistent storage.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] They need to provide fast and reliable storage for databases, root images and other data used by the containers.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] In addition to the landscape, the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF), has published other information about Kubernetes Persistent Storage including a blog helping to define the container attached storage pattern.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] This pattern can be thought of as one that uses Kubernetes itself as a component of the storage system or service.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Container Attached Storage is a type of data storage that emerged as Kubernetes gained prominence.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The Container Attached Storage approach or pattern relies on Kubernetes itself for certain capabilities while delivering primarily block, file, object and interfaces to workloads running on Kubernetes.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Common attributes of Container Attached Storage include the use of extensions to Kubernetes, such as custom resource definitions, and the use of Kubernetes itself for functions that otherwise would be separately developed and deployed for storage or data management.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Examples of functionality delivered by custom resource definitions or by Kubernetes itself include retry logic, delivered by Kubernetes itself, and the creation and maintenance of an inventory of available storage media and volumes, typically delivered via a custom resource definition.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] In Kubernetes version 1.9, the initial Alpha release of Container Storage Interface (CSI) was introduced.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Previously, storage volume plug-ins were included in the Kubernetes distribution.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] By creating a standardized CSI, the code required to interface with external storage systems was separated from the core Kubernetes code base.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Just one year later, the CSI feature was made Generally Available (GA) in Kubernetes.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] A key component of the Kubernetes control plane is the API Server, which exposes an HTTP API that can be invoked by other parts of the cluster as well as end users and external components.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] This API is a REST API and is declarative in nature, and is the same API exposed to the control plane.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The API server is backed by etcd to store all records persistently.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, all objects serve as the "record of intent" of the cluster's state, and are able to define the desired state that the writer of the object wishes for the cluster to be in.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] All objects in Kubernetes are subject to the same API conventions.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API can be extended using *Custom Resources*, which represent objects that are not part of the standard Kubernetes installation.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] These custom resources are declared using *Custom Resource Definitions* (CRDs), which is a kind of resource that can be dynamically registered and unregistered without shutting down or restarting a cluster that is currently running.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Custom controllers are another extension mechanism that interact with the Kubernetes API, similar to the default controllers in the standard pre-installed Kubernetes controller manager.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] These controllers may interact with custom resources to allow for a declarative API: users may declare the desired state of the system via the custom resources, and it is the responsibility of the custom controller to observe the change and reconcile it.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The combination of custom resources and custom controllers are often referred to as a *Kubernetes* *Operator*.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The key use case for operators are to capture the aim of a human operator who is managing a service or set of services and to implement them using automation, and with a declarative API supporting this automation.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Human operators who look after specific applications and services have deep knowledge of how the system ought to behave, how to deploy it, and how to react if there are problems.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Examples of problems solved by operators include taking and restoring backups of that application's state, and handling upgrades of the application code alongside related changes such as database schemas or extra configuration settings.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Several notable projects under the Cloud Native Computing Foundation's incubation program follow the operator pattern to extend Kubernetes, including Argo, Open Policy Agent and Istio.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines the following strategies for controlling access to its API.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API server listens on a TCP port that serves HTTPS traffic, in order to enforce transport layer security (TLS) using CA certificates.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] In older versions of Kubernetes, the API server supported listening on both HTTP and HTTPS ports (with the HTTP port number having no transport security whatsoever).
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] This was deprecated in v1.10 and eventually dropped support in v1.20 of Kubernetes.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Users are typically expected to indicate and define cluster URL details along with the necessary credentials in a *kubeconfig* file, which are natively supported by other Kubernetes tools like kubectl and the official Kubernetes client libraries.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] *Attribute-based access control (ABAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users through the use of defined access control policies which combine attributes together.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] *Role-based access control (RBAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users based on roles that are granted to the user, where each role defines a list of actions that are allowed.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] *Webhook mode*: Queries a REST API service to determine if a user is authorized to perform a given action.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The same API design principles have been used to define an API to harness a program in order to create, configure, and manage Kubernetes clusters.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] A key concept embodied in the API is using Infrastructure as Software, or the notion that the Kubernetes cluster infrastructure is itself a resource / object that can be managed just like any other Kubernetes resources.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Similarly, machines that make up the cluster are also treated as a Kubernetes resource.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The API has two pieces – the core API, and a provider implementation.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] The provider implementation consists of cloud-provider specific functions that let Kubernetes provide the cluster API in a fashion that is well-integrated with the cloud-provider's services and resources.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Kubernetes is commonly used as a way to host a microservice-based implementation, because it and its associated ecosystem of tools provide all the capabilities needed to address key concerns of any microservice architecture.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] A common criticism of Kubernetes is that it is too complex.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] Various vendors offer Kubernetes-based platforms or infrastructure as a service (IaaS) that deploy Kubernetes.
[src:skaffold/kubernetes] These are typically categorized according to open-source, commercial or managed distributions.
[src:skaffold/page] You are viewing the Skaffold v2 documentation.
[src:skaffold/page] View the archived v1 documentation here.
[src:skaffold/page] Skaffold is a command line tool that facilitates continuous development for container based & Kubernetes applications.
[src:skaffold/page] Skaffold handles the workflow for building, pushing, and deploying your application, and provides building blocks for creating CI/CD pipelines.
[src:skaffold/page] This enables you to focus on iterating on your application locally while Skaffold continuously deploys to your local or remote Kubernetes cluster, local Docker environment or Cloud Run project.
[src:skaffold/page] Skaffold simplifies your development workflow by organizing common development stages into one simple command.
[src:skaffold/page] The pluggable architecture is central to Skaffold’s design, allowing you to use your preferred tool or technology in each stage.
[src:skaffold/page] Also, Skaffold’s `profiles` feature grants you the freedom to switch tools on the fly with a simple flag.
[src:skaffold/page] For example, if you are coding on a local machine, you can configure Skaffold to build artifacts with your local Docker daemon and deploy them to minikube using `kubectl`.
[src:skaffold/page] When you finalize your design, you can switch to your production profile and start building with Google Cloud Build and deploy with Helm.
[src:skaffold/pipeline-stages] When you start Skaffold, it collects source code in your project and builds artifacts with the tool of your choice; the artifacts, once successfully built, are tagged as you see fit and pushed to the repository you specify.
[src:skaffold/pipeline-stages] In the end of the workflow, Skaffold also helps you deploy the artifacts to your Kubernetes cluster, once again using the tools you prefer.
[src:skaffold/pipeline-stages] If, for example, you run Kubernetes locally with Minikube, Skaffold will not push artifacts to a remote repository.
[src:skaffold/quickstart] Follow this tutorial if you’re using the Skaffold standalone binary.
[src:skaffold/quickstart] It walks through running Skaffold on a small Kubernetes app built with Docker inside minikube and deployed with kubectl.
[src:skaffold/quickstart] This tutorial requires Skaffold, minikube, and kubectl.
[src:skaffold/quickstart] This tutorial uses minikube because Skaffold knows how to build the app using the Docker daemon hosted inside minikube.
[src:skaffold/quickstart] This means we don’t need a registry to host the app’s container images.
[src:skaffold/quickstart] Let’s get a sample application set up to use Skaffold.
[src:skaffold/quickstart] Change to the `examples/buildpacks-node-tutorial` directory.
[src:skaffold/quickstart] Your working directory is the application directory, `skaffold/examples/buildpacks-node-tutorial`.
[src:skaffold/quickstart] This will be our root Skaffold directory.
[src:skaffold/quickstart] This sample application is written in Node, but Skaffold is language-agnostic and works with any containerized application.
[src:skaffold/quickstart] When prompted to choose the builder, press enter to accept the default selection.
[src:skaffold/quickstart] When asked which builders you would like to create Kubernetes resources for, press enter to accept the default selection.
[src:skaffold/quickstart] When asked if you want to write this configuration to skaffold.yaml, type “y” for yes.
[src:skaffold/quickstart] Open your new **skaffold.yaml**, generated at `skaffold/examples/buildpacks-node-tutorial/skaffold.yaml`.
[src:skaffold/quickstart] All of your Skaffold configuration lives in this file.
[src:skaffold/quickstart] We will go into more detail about how it works in later steps.
[src:skaffold/quickstart] Skaffold speeds up your development loop by automatically building and deploying the application whenever your code changes.
[src:skaffold/quickstart] Open `skaffold/examples/buildpacks-node-tutorial/src/index.js` and change line 10 to the following: Notice how Skaffold automatically hot reloads your code changes to your application running in minikube, intelligently syncing only the file you changed.
[src:skaffold/quickstart] app.listen(port, () => console.log(`Example app listening on port ${port}!
[src:skaffold/quickstart] While Skaffold shines for continuous development, it can also be used for continuous integration (CI).
[src:skaffold/quickstart] Let’s use Skaffold to build and test a container image.
[src:skaffold/quickstart] Your CI pipelines can run `skaffold build` to build, tag, and push your container images to a registry.
[src:skaffold/quickstart] Skaffold can also run tests against your images before deploying them.
[src:skaffold/quickstart] Let’s try this out by creating a simple custom test.
[src:skaffold/quickstart] Let’s learn how Skaffold can handle continuous delivery (CD).
[src:skaffold/quickstart] For GitOps delivery workflows, you may want to decompose your deployments into separate render and apply phases.
[src:skaffold/quickstart] That way, you can commit your hydrated Kubernetes manifests to source control before they are applied.
[src:skaffold/quickstart] You have now successfully deployed your application in two ways.
[src:skaffold/quickstart] You have learned how to use Skaffold for continuous development, integration, and delivery.
